passages.text: Reiterate Rating: NEUTRAL | PO: 9.00 NOK | Price: 8.25 NOK

We reiterate our Neutral rating on AutoStore as despite the beat and its attractive margin profile, we see 1) uncertainty regarding the new 'AutoStore as a Service' business model and the share it will represent in coming quarters, materially impacting certainty around revenues/EBIT, in our view. 2) AaaS can also weigh on FCF in the coming years given the shift to a Capex driven leasing like model. 3) The demand environment remains weak, though we have seen initial signs of improving activity in US warehouse automation from peers and AutoStore flagged increased clarity on tariffs helping customer decision making. We prefer KION (Buy) for exposure to Warehouse Automation (see our latest note here). AutoStore trades at c16x EV/EBITA FY2 a c10% discount to its historical average but we see the lack of detail on the new sales model weighing on investor sentiment. We raise our EBIT 2026/27E by c10% on a lower AaaS share than previously expected and now value AutoStore in line with quality (previously) 20% discount) peers given the company's high margin profile and first signs of an improvement in US warehouse automation demand. Our PO moves to NOK9.

2Q25 revenues of \(\) 133.9\(m were 38% ahead of consensus, supported by the AutoStore as a Service share being lower than anticipated at\) \mathtt{c5\%} \(vs\) \mathtt{c20\%} \(in 1Q25. AutoStore signed AaaS contracts of\) \ \(6.9m\) in 2Q25, significantly lower than the \(\) 27m\(in 1Q25. Going forward we expect uncertainty around the share of AaaS to persist, likely driving further earnings volatility. Orders declined\) \mathtt{c10\%} \(oragonically YoY but were supported by a\) +16\% \(FX impact from weaker US\).

With AaaS, AutoStore offers its customer to pay for the system with quarterly instalments over the course of c7- 10 years. While this should support higher recurring revenues mid- term it drives lower revs & FCF near term, as revenues are recognized over the course of multiple years. Going forward, we expect an AaaS share in revenues of c15%, but uncertainty persists, given mgmt does not guide the expected share.

AutoStore currently trades on c16x EV/EBITA FY2 on our estimates, c10% discount to the average since IPO in late 2021. The company has seen growth forecasts significantly deteriorate over past years & earnings are at risk of pressure over the coming quarters.

While this should support higher recurring revenues over coming years it is in- taining the current pressure on earnings, as revenues are recognized over the course of multiple years instead of in

AutoStore will account for the delivered systems as a set on its own balance sheet and will account for costs by depreciating these assets. Cash inflows will occur over the contract period and thereby delay the company's cash generation. As of now, the share of AaaS of sales fluctuates substantially with \(c20\%\) in 1Q25 and \(c5\%\) in 2Q25. We think AaaS offers attractive payment conditions for AutoStore's customers and forecast \(c15\%\) of new projects to fall under AaaS. As the company is still new to the new sales structure, management does not guide on their expectations on uptake of the solutions as of now.

In 1Q25, AaaS made up \(c20\%\) of revenues, \(c5\%\) in 2Q25 and we forecast \(c15\%\) going forward. As an example, should the company generate quarterly revenues of 100 but now generate \(15\%\) of these revenues via the AaaS approach, the company will only book 85 revenues in the first quarter. Around two quarters later, the company will start to book the first quarterly revenue share from the \(15\%\) AaaS revenues. We currently assume a revenue break even period of six years, faster than the overall contract length of around 7- 10 years. Hence, the shift to an AaaS solutions negatively impacts earnings for the first few years but should overall be accretive in the longer run.
Cash generation will be slowed down, as AutoStore will bear the costs of production for a longer time before recovering cash via the quarterly instalments.

AutoStore currently trades on c16x EV/EBITA FY2 on our forecasts. While this is a c10% discount to its average since it listed in late 2021 on our estimates, the company has seen growth forecasts significantly deteriorating over past years. While the company guided for c40% revenue CAGR going forward at its CMD in 2022, management took a more conservative approach in 2024 and did not give revenue growth guidance post FY24. Customer investment uncertainty and the new AutoStore as a Service business model are likely to weigh on near term earnings.

We derive our PO of NOK9 by valuing AutoStore in line with quality peers at 19x EV/EBITA 2026E and discount 12 months. We think an in line valuation is justified given the company's high margin profile and potential for a demand recovery though timing remains uncertain.

We value AutoStore in line with the quality industrials peers multiple of 19x 2026E adjusted EBIT and discount back 12m. We believe this is fair given AutoStore is a high margin business but has limited visibility on revenue growth in the near- term. Our PO is NOK 9.
Upside risks are faster- than- expected growth in warehouse automation, higher online penetration rates driving growth in eCommerce, higher- than- expected growth rates within Cubic Storage.
Downside risks are lower- than- expected growth in warehouse automation penetration rates, quality issues with AutoStore systems, and weakening demand.

Our price objective of EUR67 is based on KION's historical average multiple of 11.5x EV/EBITA on 2026 estimates and discount 12m. We think the in line valuation is fair given the improved outlook especially for European short cycle.
Risks to our price objective are a rapid slowdown in the forklift market and an even further elongated push- out of warehouse automation projects.
